# Phase 0 / Phase 1: local server uses SQLite, one file on disk.
DATABASE_URL="file:./dev.db"

# Phase 4 adds a second connection string for the VPS deployment
# (PostgreSQL via Supabase) — not used by the local server at all. This is
# the VPS process's OWN .env, never the restaurant PC's.
#
# Supabase gives you two connection strings per project (Project Settings →
# Database): a direct connection (port 5432) and a pooled one via PgBouncer
# (port 6543). Prisma needs the POOLED one here (`?pgbouncer=true`) because
# the VPS Fastify process, like any serverless-shaped/long-lived Node app,
# can open more connections than Supabase's small free-tier direct-connection
# limit allows — see docs/deployment-setup.md's "VPS server deployment"
# section for the full setup walkthrough.
# DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.xxxx:PASSWORD@aws-0-region.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1"

# Shared secret the local server signs its service JWT with, and the VPS
# verifies with — distinct from JWT_SECRET (staff sessions). Generate a real
# random value for production, e.g. `openssl rand -hex 32`.
# VPS_SYNC_SECRET="change-me"

# Port the VPS Fastify instance listens on (host is always 0.0.0.0 — see
# src/vps/server.ts).
# VPS_PORT=5000
